< Review>
What a great new place to grab a drink and watch the game. I went here with my friend and had some delicious craft beers on tap. We ordered food and it was really tasty. We shared our food, but I liked the bourbon burger the most, great sauce and the bun is so good. There is a large projector so everyone can see the game, and the atmosphere is really open with a half wall separating the bar from the viewing area. Top notch place, I'll be coming back.< /Review>
<Pics>None<//Pics><Resp>None</Resp><GmapID>0x809ad21ec5e03fc9:0x76620592dad59450< /GmapID></record></dataset><record>
< rating>
1<//rating>
< Review>
This review is in lieu of shouting at whatever poor employee happened to have picked up the phone.  Whoever it was that picked up got spared because my son started crying - good thing, I suppose, since it probably wasn't her fault.

Got 2 burgers. Bacon and Blue with kettle chips and Bourbon with fries.

Ordered over the phone. Girl was nice enough but not really on top of her game.  Asked me for my order then said hang on let me get a pen.....after I'd already given her the order. So, I tell her again. Then she tries to confirm it and gets it wrong. Nothing big just she said medium done when I wanted well done. No biggie.

Problems came when my husband got home with the food. His kettle chips were burnt and inedible and he had no cheese on his bacon and Blue.  It's in the name for crying out loud! Then my burger didn't have any of the bourbon sauce, or so I thought. Looked dry, none on inside of either bin. Then I picked it up. Sauce under the burger in the to-go box. My bun was just sitting in it. Then to top it all off and had me calling in were the hairs I found stuck to my fries! Just two but still!

I'd been wanting to try them out since they opened but hadn't been able too. I was so disappointed.
WE will not be eating here again.</Review>

<Review>I had a new stereo receiver put into my car. It took about 4 hours total, and as far as I can tell everything works great. They are an official dealer for Alpine, which comes with some perks if you buy into that brand of stereo. These include service, and an extended warranty.

I would be lying if I said the prices here are cheap; but they are for the most part fair. I got the base level Alpine CDE-151 receiver for $150, which is exactly what Alpine sells them for online, however you can get the same model on amazon for ~$90. I ended up paying about $60 in other parts required for installation (dash kit, wire harness, and antenna adapter), and $90 for labor. There was also a $7 miscellaneous charge which I am unsure of the cause.

As far as customer service goes, 10/10. The owner, David, showed me all the different options and explained the strengths and weaknesses of each unit to help me decide what I was looking for. There was never any pressure to buy more expensive models, which I really appreciate. He and his staff are very friendly and knowledgeable.< /Review>< Resp>

Clint Backes</user_name>
< text>
I came in to Lombards knowing what I wanted to do and I was given a range of options for a simple stealth modification install of an 8 in sub and a micro amp to a 2016 rav4.
The owner, David,  gave me the rundown and was to the point. They have a lot of options to the work being done. If you want the best in quality sound, you're going to pick the best wiring, which they offer at half off retail.
David was kind and informative and listened to all my stories without being pushy with the sale. I scheduled an appointment that he was able to bump up a day for me and even gave me a ride up the grade while they did the work.
I came from Oakland to get this service because you don't get this kind of quality service and experience in the city. They just want to push you thru so the next customer can give them money.
Quality service.
Quality experience.

The only complaint I have is their no refund policy.
I can see it being necessary for installed components. But a single battery bank for jump starting a vehicle that doesn't work should qualify for a refund, since it was not an installed item, but a seperate item.
Dick move on their part, but they made good by offering an alternative to the $160 in the form of a new car battery for another vehicle.
Thank you.<//text>

5< /rate>
< Review>
I had no idea about car sound systems. I walked into the store just to get an idea about the different types and brands of speakers available besides the ever popular Bose speakers.
I simply strolled into the store and was lucky to meet with the owner David Joy. I asked him to explain to me about how to recognize what is a good speaker and what will be good for what I need. I showed him my car and what I had in it for speakers. He then spent about 90 minutes explaining to me everything that I possibly wanted to know and more. I was extremely pleased with his customer service. I don't think a Best Buy or any other sound system store would spend that much time with a customer.
I eventually got Audison Prima speakers and amplifier, obviously there were more expensive ones but David knew what I was looking for, he showed me cheaper options and played sample music to show me the how different musical instruments and vocals sound on the speakers with and without amplifiers. I must say I was able to make a very educated decision to invest in the sound system I bought. The installation was immaculate, the upholstery on the subwoofer matched that of the car. The rear speakers were perfectly recessed into the rear wall with similar colored grill, very good workmanship.
If you are an entry level customer who do not know much about speakers, amplifiers and stereo systems then LOMBARD Stereos is the place to go in town. I got what I paid for and will definitely go back if I plan to change my stereo system. I was a very satisfied customer. Definitely ask for David if he is in the store.</Review>

Heidi Shaw< /name>
<Time>1583840701060< /Time><rate>5<//rate>< review>
The lentil soup is so delicious here, I got two to take home with me!!  I had visitors in town who were catching a plane the same night I decided to try this restaurant for the first time.  I wasn't sure it was a safe bet since I hadn't been here before, but a first glance at the menu and seeing all of the activity on the patio led me to believe it was worth a first try.  This is one of those places where you wish you could give 10 stars.  It feels like a well established, family-friendly, romantic couples date night, girls night out gathering kind of place.  There is something for everyone.   Even your dog has two dining options on the menu.  The wait staff was sensitive to our need to hurry in order to get to the airport and while they were more rushed with our table than they normally would be, they didn't make us FEEL rushed.  We enjoyed a wonderful dining experience and left feeling very satisfied.  10 star experience all around.</review>

<Name>Ochs Millard<//Name>< Date>
1549854530600<//Date>
<Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
No reason to ever fell the need to fly to Italy for a meal.
Piazza 1909 provides the right ambience to make you feel you are in Italy especially if you ask to sit inside. Now let me discuss the food.  It is truly amazing.  It brought tears to my wife as she reminisce about the stuffed calamari like her mother used to make.  But when we had the gnocchi with Gorgonzola we were lifted to even a higher experience.  Gnocchi should be small and light as a pillow. Often difficult to find in restaurants but at1909 the chef can be seen making the gnocchi while you dine and truly has mastered the touch through his family generations.
Congratulations to piazza 1909 to the manager the waiter and support staff. A job well done.  To the chef simply amazing and looking forward to our next dining experience. Also I plan to take a cooking lesson that is offered by the Grandmother at Piazza 1909.  Great to see  a family owned restaurant share their passion and love for the art of cooking.< /Text>

<Pictures>None</Pictures>< Text>
Just returned from Italy (again) and felt this restaurant was as close to a good ristorante is like in Sardegna or Firenze.  The bolognese was rich, complex and creamy as the best we have experience. And the cinghiale (wild boar)  brought back memories of the mountain village of Pattada.  Service was as close to Italian we seen in the state: attentive, but not pushy.  And while we chose to eat inside, the noise level was low enough we could comfortably talk to each other.  Also can recommend il dolce volcano and the portobello cocktail. (Overall, food at several of the other La Jolla restaurants were completely unmemorable. )< /Text>

< gmap_id>
0x80dc03e4b9bc52e7:0xfc907283e276033d<//gmap_id>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Text>
Piazza 1909 is tremendously underwhelming, even if that's not saying anything new for an Italian restaurant in San Diego. San Diego has an Italian restaurant problem and, unfortunately, Piazza 1909 is not an outlier.

This place has food issues, which I will get to in a minute. I want to start with service issues first, as those are more basic and speak to "Restaurant Management 101" misses. I waited 7 minutes at the beginning of the meal for my server to acknowledge me and take my drink order despite Piazza 1909 being empty.

Once he came by, I ordered the coconut water (purportedly in its own shell) only to be told after 5 minutes by my returning waiter that they didn't have it today. This is a problem. At minimum, if an item is not available, the server should tell the diner when menus are set down -- it should never be a surprise to the server that the restaurant is not able to fulfill an item on the menu, ESPECIALLY at the beginning of the evening. I was seated at around 5:30pm - and I suspect this place rarely, if ever, carries this item despite its presence on their menu. Unacceptable.

I waited another 10 minutes at the end of my meal in between the time my server took my credit card and returned a signable receipt. I gave him the stink-eye across the room at one point and he recognized it and understood, but he never apologized. Again, unacceptable.

For food, I ordered the Bruschetta, which was alright, I guess. I like my tomatoes a tad sweeter and less tart on bruschetta, and I could not really discern much balsamic, which typically holds this dish together for me. Also, the crostini was crunchy, but had a weird, almost "stale-like" texture.

Commendably, their lasagna didn't have ricotta (which is why I ordered it, as ricotta-less lasagna is guaranteed to be closer to the "real-deal"). Unfortunately, it also didn't have much flavor. It consisted of their "beef ragout" sauce, some very light almost nonexistent b√©chamel, and thin wispy lasagna sheets. Everything was overpowered by their crappy beef sauce, which was bland and boring.

More troubling, the center of the lasagna was not heated to a proper safe temperature. In fact, it was served to me at room temperature, which is worse in my opinion than if it were cold, as it raised concerns that Piazza 1909 was perhaps storing the lasagna at room temperature before an all-too-brief reheat rather than storing it in a properly-refrigerated space.

Chef Stefano Ceresoli may have an Italian name, but he has lost his way, assuming he was ever qualified enough to cook in Italy to begin with. From my experience, this food would not fly in Italy. It would not fly in NYC. It would not fly in Chicago. It would not fly in Bugtussle, Kentucky. Honestly, San Diego is one of the few American cities where a place like this could conceivably remain open in.

My waiter asked if I wanted dessert? No thanks!!!<//Text>

113055764265992275547</user>
<review>We get it, California, you like sourdough. But sourdough croissants?? No. Literally everything here is sourdough. Every. Item. I am constantly on the search for fresh baked bread, but no options other than sourdough here, and always a long line.  Pizzas are pure oil. Chocolate Chip cookies are decent.</review><rating>2</rating><time>1621616858255</time><Gmap_id>0x808f874190045807:0x2eeb5a2233b2e795</Gmap_id>< name>
Jason Orlic< /name>
<response>None</response>< pictures>
None<//pictures>
</record>
</dataset><record>
< Text>
Arizmendi Bakery has been one of my favorite bakeries to frequent since living in Oakland. It is a cooperative business‚Äîanotherwords, run by the people that work there.

They are very Covid minded. You line up outside the store front. You can look into the storefront window to see what pastries are available. When you get to the head of the line there is a list on the door telling you what pizza and soup is available for the day. The cookies were bundled together for easier buying.

There were 2 people working the front of the store‚Äîone taking the order and money, and the other person getting it and bagging for you.

Their baked goods are fresh and delicious! I have always scarfed down their vegetarien soup and pizza with gusto. Their prices are reasonable.

They look like they are succussful during the pandemic, and I am happy to see that. There are many businesses very close by that haven't been able to make it.</Text>
<gmap_id>0x808f874190045807:0x2eeb5a2233b2e795</gmap_id><UserId.>101872002843208272758< /UserId.>< username>

If you are living you haven't lived till you ate here. I have no clue what I was doing, I got in line and said today we eat something different. If you come to Oakland, and don't do anything, and want to discover the meaning of life or gain a new perspective, come here grab a bite and watch your world shift.</text>

< Date>

< Rating>
5<//Rating>
<Review>Arizmendi is a democratically run, worker-owned cooperative, which in itself is super cool! All the workers share in the profits. They make good money!

But you may be more interested in knowing that they sell absolutely delicious pizza, bread, pastries, and soups. Everything is as good as it gets. They have a long history of excellence and are not slowing down one bit!

You may also be interested in knowing that, because the workers don't need tips, but people are used to tipping, they keep a "tip jar" by the register and donate the money that comes in to a local non-profit. The non-profit changes monthly. You can always find information about the current beneficiary of the tip jar money by reading the walls.<//Review><pics>None</pics>< Resp>
None<//Resp>

<user_name>K C</user_name>< text>
I've never been dissapointed coming here!  If you love a good crusty sourdough like me, then you must try Arizmendi! I'll confess it's not the best SD loaf I've had but pretty close to it and only because the Bay Area has too many choices which make the SD competition stiff here. They do, however, make the best heavenly sourdough pizza on earth and offer a delicious daily vegetarian soup that will leave you with a very difficult choice to make.

As for the baked goodies, the almond flour brownie is the best brownie I've ever had and it's gluten free!?! But don't let that keep you from trying it...I couldn't't believe I actually found a GF item I like. Even my kids approve!  Unfortunately, the Lakeshore location is the only one selling it but don't worry any pastry at Arizmendi is great. Croissants are flaky and buttery, cookies are chewy and fresh... You can't go wrong with Arizmendi on any given day.</text>

< username>
N B<//username>
< review>
Varied and delicious selection of cookies, scones, cinnamon roll-type things, muffins, rolls (savory and sweet), and loaves of bread. I especially enjoyed their cheese scone... very crumbly yet moist with all the right savory tones without being too salty. The area to grab bakes goods can get a little cramped with very few people, so it's ideal to nab what you want as quickly as you can! The sweet baguette is nice, but best fresh. The crispy skin can get soft within a few hours, but while it is crisp, it is extra good! (Also they had quite a few gluten-free options for various products!)

There is a fridge full of various salad options (both leafy and other e.g. bean salad), cold soup (I think only 1 kind), and a small selection of cheese. Excellent for a quick baguette + cheese snack or picnic meal.

Lots of drinks available on their menu and decent amount of indoor seating. The entryway can get cramped with the line (it's a busy place!) so come ready with some "excuse me" and "pardon me"s to squeeze past other patrons.

See the photo: 10% discount for 60+ y.o. with bike helmets!<//review>

<Text>You gotta love a local co-op (read: worker owned & operated for you non-socialist types) bakery just for the sake of that. One of my favourite bakeries in the East Bay!  I usually make the exit to load up on sweet and savory baked goods prior to the long haul home to Los Angeles.

I've been a regular customer over the past 15 years and I haven't been disappointed.  It is a co-op bakery that is self-service.  All items contain no artificial flavours/ingredients and taste excellent fresh or reheated in the oven.</text>

AMAZING PIZZA. All vegetarian and it's so good I bring my non-vegetarian friends here and even they're blown away.

They serve one type of pizza daily, different each day. I don't bother with looking at the menu because I have never once been disappointed by what they serve. You can by the slice, half a pizza, or a whole pizza.

<text>I've lived in the bay area for quite some time now and I'm ashamed to say I've never been here.  You will walk in and instantly be overwhelmed with sights and smells.  It smells amazing, it smells like baked goods and coffee.  The 2 best things in life.  I went during the lunch rush hour and that's probably why I was so overwhelmed.

When you walk in, to the left, there's a wall full of amazing baked goods such as cookies, loaves of bread, focaccia bread, scones, muffins, brownies, and so much more.  Any delicious carb you can think of, they have it here.  They even have a bread schedule, on certain days they bake certain breads.  There was sooooo much I wanted to try.  For times sake I grabbed a cookie that had chocolate chips, coconut, oatmeal and some other amazing things.  I also got a slice of the pizza of the day.  They only offer one kind of pizza per day, by the slice or you can buy an entire pie.  When I went they were serving an Indian pizza with Masala sauce and cilantro! Soooooooooo delicious.

It is sweet/savory heaven here.  They offer a variety of teas and coffees as well.  I can't wait to go back and try some of their other baked goods.  I hear the granola is the best in town.  Pricing isn't bad, service is good, and just a bit hectic and chaotic inside.  That's just means it's good right?<//text>< Pics>

< user>
116207656982980496075</user>
<user_name>Bruce Langley<//user_name><time>1493893957239</time>< rating>
2< /rating>
< text>
After four years of wanting to support this worker owned cooperative, I've thrown in the towel.
The customer service area is poorly laid out requiring one to stand in up to three different lines for one sitting.
Some bakery items are prepared inconsistently, items with crusts are often baked too hard to enjoy, as one reviewer noted of the baguettes. Soft baked goods like focaccio are usually good though.
Self service coffee urns often run out with no standby urns brewing, meaning long waits for an item that has already been paid for. (the irony of being offered a senior discount and a bicycle helmet wearer's discount on a purchase where the product was not delivered is not lost upon me).
The daily pizza is quite good. They have a new ingredient combination each day, meaning a fresh, hot delicious surprise everytime I come in.  Trouble is that my order gets dropped too often, somewhere between the cashier and the person preparing and serving the slices, one who works six feet away from the other.
The last time I was in (the very last time) I concluded that if I wanted food service like this, I should re-enlist in the Navy.<//text>

<user>107933432659463763637<//user><user_name>Vivian Chan< /user_name><Date>1445411339070</Date>< rate>
5</rate>
< Review>
I've been going to this place since high school--amazing pizzas, delicious pastries. The saddest time was taking a friend here when they were remodeling and closed.

This is the place that has locals coming back time and time again--it's on the list of nearly everyone who've moved to other places and have a bucket list each time they visit.

Favorites: Chocolate Thing, Olive Focaccia, Cheese Rolls, Corn Cherry Scone, Corn Muffins, Pizza--anykind.
Good to know: the baguettes are not your typical french baguette--they are hearty, sourdough with a substantial crust, so be ready.

There's often a line but it'll move fast. And they take credit card so all the easier to carry away a big box of pastries.</Review>
